Dorsal cirri digitiform, basally attached to dorsal ligule on anterior chaetigers, about as long as dorsal ligule (
Fig. 6A–B
), subdistally attached to dorsal ligule on mid-body to posterior chaetigers, about 0.8 times as long as dorsal ligule on mid-body chaetigers (
Fig. 6C–D
), about 0.4–0.5 times as long as dorsal ligule on posterior chaetigers (
Fig. 6E
), distally attached to dorsal ligule on last 13 chaetigers, about 0.5 times as long as dorsal ligule (
Fig. 6F
).

Dorsal ligules subconical on anterior chaetigers (
Fig. 6A–B
), becoming small pennant-like lobe on middle of mid-body to anterior half of posterior chaetigers (
Fig. 6C–E
); base of dorsal ligule slightly elongate and broader on mid-body chaetigers (
Fig. 6D
), markedly elongate and broader on posterior chaetigers (
Fig. 6E–F
). Notopodial prechaetal lobe absent.

Median ligule conical on anterior-most chaetigers, shorter than neuroacicular ligule (
Fig. 6A–B
), subconical thereafter and longer than neuroacicular ligule (
Fig. 6C–F
).

Neuroacicular ligule with predominant inferior lobe on anterior to anterior half of posterior chaetigers (
Fig. 6A–E
), inferior and superior lobes subequal in length on last 13 chaetigers (
Fig. 6F
), about 1.3 times longer than ventral ligule on anterior to mid-body chaetigers, about as long as ventral ligule on posterior chaetigers (
Fig. 6A–F
). Neuropodial postchaetal lobe present throughout. Ventral ligule subconical throughout. Ventral cirri mid-ventrally attached to ventral edge of parapodia, about 0.8 times as long as ventral ligule on anterior chaetigers, about 0.7 times as long as ventral ligule on mid-body chaetigers, about 0.5 times as long as ventral ligule on posterior chaetigers (
Fig. 6A–F
).

Notochaetae present from chaetiger 3 to posterior chaetigers, homogomph spinigers present throughout (
Fig. 7A
). Supra-acicular fascicle of neuropodia: homogomph spinigers and short-bladed heterogomph falcigers with serrations present throughout (
Fig. 7B–C
). Subacicular fascicle of neuropodia: short-bladed heterogomph falcigers with serrations present throughout (
Fig. 7D
), heterogomph spinigers absent throughout (
Fig. 7E
).
